showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3258.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Introduction to Roleplaying</span><hr size=1> Caillou---Perhaps /tell is something you would use in EQ, but I wrote this based on text-RPing, where folks emoted thoughts all the time. When everything you do is written (ie no visual graphics), then you go into much deeper detail, and the *point* of emoting thoughts is to give players an idea of the inner workings of your character. I.e. if you play a hardass all the time, but your character is truly a big softy, then without using &quot;thought&quot; your character will only appear to be a hardass. Character development is heighted by the &quot;thoughts&quot; of RP. When your characters are so intertwined with other characters in a text RPG, thoughts very much come into play as part of the entertainment value and to help other players know how to write your character properly in involved storylines. <br>
<br>
EQ doesn't provide that depth of RP, so I don't use thought a lot here, since usually people do just that: use the thought as IC knowledge. But in my previous guild, thought *was* used as it was pretty intensive RP about deceit and manipulation. Without the other players knowing my character's thoughts, the entertainment value is lost because they can't see the manipulation as it happens. Perhaps thought is the wrong word---what I mean to convey is that there are some things, even gestures, done for which very clear cues are given in the emote to show the other player that his or her character is not supposed to react to it---at this juncture, at least. Later, when events unfold, that character might think back on things and say, &quot;ooh, that's what was going on back then...&quot; <br>
<br>
