<br>
An example might be; Isharra says &quot;I'll be fine, tend to the others&quot; /em The look in her eyes betrays the pain she feels from the wound on her leg<br>
<br>
Now, you can choose NOT to betray your emotions, but to do so and not expect a reaction to them would be a bit unfair to your fellows. If you Act like you are tough, but React in a way that betrays your &quot;true feelings&quot; the person who you are roleplaying with has a choice to react accordingly, with information they have. They don't have to filter out information they are not supposed to have, but you gave to them 3 seconds earlier. <br>
<br>
There is a difference between telling a story, and acting out a story. That is all in the perspective of the audience. When roleplaying, there is no audience, there are only actors. As there is no script, all the actors take cues from their co-stars. Meta Character/Game info, that may be part of the story you are trying to tell, is only known by you. If you want to let your fellow actors know these things through dramatic play, it has to be done in character. <br>
<br>
My rule of thumb is this, Say is used to act. /emote is used to react. If you choose to use /emote to act, it has to be consistant with your other actions, because the other players will read it as a reaction, and act accordingly. <br>
